{"questionId":"10403","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Both vinegar (a dilute aqueous solution of ethanoic acid) and bleach are used as cleaning agents.</span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Bleach reacts with ammonia, also used as a cleaning agent, to produce the poisonous compound chloramine, NH<sub>2</sub>Cl.</span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">State the hybridization of the nitrogen atom in chloramine.</span></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">sp<sup>3</sup> &nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>[✔]</strong></span></p>","meta":{"questionId":"10403","referenceCode":"19M.2.hl.TZ1.5c(ii)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"State the hybridization of the nitrogen atom in chloramine.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c(ii)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 14: Chemical bonding and structure","14.2 Hybridization","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 14: Chemical bonding and structure"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}